## Scenarios and How to Handle Them

### "I wrote a lot and want to commit it all at once"

Do not. Break your work into the individual logical units it represents and commit them separately. Use `git add -p` (patch mode) to stage individual hunks if multiple changes are in the same file.

```bash
git add -p src/api/assets/index.ts   # Stage only specific changes in a file
```

### "The tests are flaky and sometimes fail for unrelated reasons"

Fix the flaky tests before committing. A flaky test is a broken test. If a test fails intermittently, it cannot be trusted, and it means there is a real problem with either the test or the system under test.

### "`vp check` fails on a file I didn't touch"

This means the codebase already had a lint or type error before your change. Fix it in a separate preceding commit (`fix: resolve pre-existing lint error in ...`), then make your change commit.

### "I need to commit just to save my work"

Use a feature branch. You can commit broken work on a feature branch, but it must be cleaned up (squashed or amended) before the branch is merged. Never push broken commits to `develop` or `main`.

```bash
git checkout -b feature/my-work
git commit -m "wip: asset create form (do not merge)"  # acceptable on a feature branch
# ... continue working ...
git commit --amend   # fix the WIP commit before merging
```

### "An AI agent produced a large batch of code and wants to commit it all"

The AI agent must split its output into individual commits per the commit discipline rules. If the agent cannot run `vp check` and `vp test`, the human developer must run them before committing the agent's output.

### "A test is failing because of something I didn't change"

This is a regression introduced by a previous commit. Fix the regression before committing your new work. Do not commit on top of a broken test suite.

