## Automating the Checklist with a Git Hook

To run `vp check` and `vp test` automatically before every `git commit`:

Create `.git/hooks/pre-commit`:

```bash
#!/bin/sh

echo "Running pre-commit checks..."

# Step 1: vp check
vp check
if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then
  echo ""
  echo "❌ vp check failed. Fix the errors above before committing."
  exit 1
fi

# Step 2: vp test
vp test
if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then
  echo ""
  echo "❌ vp test failed. Fix the failing tests before committing."
  exit 1
fi

echo ""
echo "✅ Pre-commit checks passed."
```

Make it executable:

```bash
chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit
```

With this hook in place, `git commit` will automatically run both checks and abort if either fails.

**Note:** Git hooks are local and not committed to the repository. Each developer must set them up manually. Document this in the project README's "Development Setup" section.

---

## What the CI Pipeline Also Checks

Even if you skip the pre-commit checks locally, the GitLab CI pipeline will catch errors:

```yaml
check:
  script: vp check   # Fails the pipeline if check fails

test:
  script: vp test    # Fails the pipeline if tests fail
```

A failed pipeline blocks merge into `develop` or `main`. The pre-commit checklist exists so that you catch these failures locally in seconds rather than waiting for the pipeline.

---

## Summary

| Checkpoint | Command | Must Pass? |
|---|---|---|
| Format + Lint + TypeCheck | `vp check` | ✅ Yes, always |
| All Tests | `vp test` | ✅ Yes, always |
| Diff Review | `git diff --staged` | ✅ Yes, manually |
| Commit Message Format | Conventional Commits | ✅ Yes, always |
| Single Logical Unit | Manual review | ✅ Yes, always |
| No secrets staged | `git status` + review | ✅ Yes, always |
